  <h1>Beneficiary Letter — Australia</h1>
  <p><strong>Prepared for:</strong> [Borrower Name] | <strong>Date:</strong> [Date]</p>

  <h2>What is an EPM?</h2>
  <p>The Equity Preservation Mortgage (EPM) is a loan secured by your home. The loan proceeds are invested to generate monthly income for you while preserving your home equity. Unlike traditional reverse mortgages, your home is NOT sold to pay the loan.</p>

  <h2>For Your Beneficiaries</h2>
  <p>When you pass away (or when the loan ends for other reasons), your beneficiaries will inherit:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The Property:</strong> Your home (fully owned, subject to the mortgage debt)</li>
    <li><strong>The Estate:</strong> Property value MINUS the outstanding loan balance</li>
    <li><strong>NNEG Protection:</strong> If the property has fallen in value, insurance covers any shortfall. Your beneficiaries cannot inherit a debt.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Settlement Process</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Lender is notified of your passing</li>
    <li>Estate administrator contacts Lender</li>
    <li>Property is appraised (current value)</li>
    <li>Lender's loan balance is calculated</li>
    <li>If property sells, proceeds: Lender first, then beneficiaries receive remainder</li>
    <li>If property is retained, mortgage remains in place until voluntarily repaid</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>No Estate Debt</h2>
  <p>Your beneficiaries will NEVER owe more than the property is worth. NNEG insurance (No Negative Equity Guarantee) ensures this.</p>

  <h2>Tax Considerations</h2>
  <p>In Australia, inheritance is generally NOT taxable (there is no inheritance tax). However, Centrelink Age Pension impacts may apply if your beneficiaries were recipients of your pension.</p>

  <p><strong>Beneficiaries should seek independent legal and tax advice regarding estate settlement.</strong></p>
